<p>write sensually and you can forget most other rules</p>

<p>If you commit to evoking sights, sounds, smells, tastes, movements, and textures in the readerâ€™s brain, you can quit sweating the small stuff. For instance, youâ€™ve probably heard that strong verbs and specific nouns are better than adverbs and adjectives.Â     This isnâ€™t necessarily true, but it often turns out to be the caseâ€”not because modifiers are bad, but because itâ€™s easier to evoke sensations via concrete, easy-to-grasp objects and actions.    If you write, â€œhe looked at her quizzically,â€ thatâ€™s harder to instantly picture than, â€œhe cocked his headâ€ or â€œhe furrowed his brow.â€    Donâ€™t worry about adjectives and adverbs. Just work to evoke images and other sensations. Make your images strong and specific.Â </p>

<p>Should I avoid using idioms in my writing?</p>

<p>You canâ€™t. In fact, you used two of them in your question: â€œavoidâ€ means to step out of the way of a physical obstacle. Yet you used it to mean â€œrefrain from a behavior.â€ You also referred to idioms beingÂ inÂ writing, as if prose was a container. You used both â€œavoidâ€ and â€œinâ€ metaphorically, and those particular metaphors are idioms of the English language. Idioms are so bound up with the way we write and think, theyâ€™re unavoidable. Without using them, youâ€™d be incapable of expressing many ideas.
