<p>How can I avoid clichÃ©s in my writing?</p>

<p>Good writing is sensual. I donâ€™t mean sexy (though good writing can be sexy), I mean that it tickles the five senses. Sensual writing is the best way to reach people, because humans are sensual creatures. Humans live through their senses. When marks on paper evoke sensations, the effect is magical. ClichÃ©s suck, because they donâ€™t make us see, hear, smell, touch, or taste. They fail because theyâ€™re too familiar. When people read â€œevery cloud has a silver lining,â€ they probably donâ€™t imagine a cloud or see the color silver. They donâ€™t imagine running their fingers up and down a lining. Instead, itâ€™s as if the whole phrase is a word: everycloudhasasilverlining. Itâ€™s a label for an abstract idea. Whatâ€™s the abstract idea? That bad things have good sides to them. (â€œBad things have good sides to them,â€ while not interesting, is better than â€œEvery cloud has a silver lining.â€) If you want to evoke that idea with a metaphor, what are some images you could use? Images that arenâ€™t trodden flat? Try brainstorming: â€œEvery case of strep throat is an excuse to eat ice cream.â€ â€œToo bad mama died, but that black suit Iâ€™m wearing to her funeral sure is slimming.â€ Rather than avoiding clichÃ©s, which is a negative act (and thus hard to achieve), try working to make your writing as sensual as possible. As a side effect, clichÃ©s will wither and die. When I write, I go through each sentence (often each phrase) and consciously ask if Iâ€™m evoking an image: am I making the reader see a dead fly? hear the tink tink tink of a xylophone? Smell urine? Taste soup thatâ€™s so hot, it burns his tongue? Run his fingers up and down some corduroy pants?
The trick is specificity. Donâ€™t worry about being original, just be specific. What,Â exactly, are we supposed to see, hear, smell, touch or taste?</p>

