<p>The Way Forward
In Fiction Writing 101, we learned that each element must move the story forward. I agree with this, but, on itâ€™s own, that dogma is too simplistic. What does it mean to move a story forward? You can move â€œKing Kongâ€ forward by saying â€œâ€¦ and then the ape climbed the Empire State building, reached the top and was killed by airplanes.â€ If we can step forward with a sentence or two, why waste our time with ten minutes of movie, ten minutes in which only learn a few facts? A story is only a story if we move forward in a satisfying way. A trip to Paris isnâ€™t fun if weâ€™re blindfolded the whole time weâ€™re there.</p>

<p>To understand why â€œJust the facts, maâ€™amâ€ doesnâ€™t work, imagine moving a dinner forward by saying â€œSalad, then steak and potatoes, then desert,â€ without actually serving any food. That doesnâ€™t count as â€œmoving forward.â€ We havenâ€™t earned the right to proceed to the second course until weâ€™ve tasted the first.</p>

<p>Tasting is sensual, and thereâ€™s the key. Humans are sensual creatures. If we havenâ€™t seen, heard, felt, smelled or tasted a thing, we havenâ€™t experienced it. If we havenâ€™t experienced it, we canâ€™t move forward from it. Narratives arenâ€™t simply about moving forward; they are about moving forward from one sensual experience to the next.</p>

<p>When we sensualize our stories, we arenâ€™t adding spice to them. Sensation isnâ€™t spice; itâ€™s the world. It doesnâ€™t sit on top of the world. It IS the world. In the world, nothing is general, abstract or featureless. There is no such thing as love. There is only the specific love that Charlie feels for Sarah. And Charlie is not a man. Heâ€™s a specific man with flaking skin on his shoulders, from a day at the Coney Island beach. And we hear the clack, clack, clack of Sarahâ€™s heels on the bathroom floor, which is what makes her an actual woman.</p>

<p>We can infuse our stories with sensuality in many ways, the two main ones being via specific details about whatâ€™s actually happening and metaphor:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>He rubbed his palm over the gnarled surface.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>The ship was bigger than four ocean liners laid end to end.</p>
  </li>
