<p>Itâ€™s not enough to say â€œIt was a really big ship.â€ That doesnâ€™t move the story forward, because â€œa really big shipâ€ is a cheat. Itâ€™s like claiming youâ€™ve actually given your son a birthday present when youâ€™ve given him socks. Any kid will tell you socks donâ€™t count as a present (nor does â€œmoney for collegeâ€). Itâ€™s like skipping to sex by saying â€œforeplayâ€ instead of actually kissing an caressing. We have to earn each forward step by sensualizing the moment weâ€™re currently in.</p>

<p>There are a couple of traps to look out for: the first is cliche. â€œCold as winterâ€ isnâ€™t sensual, because weâ€™ve heard it too many times. We read it as coldaswinter, and it doesnâ€™t spark any sensation in our brains. â€œColder than a witches titâ€ is just as bad. Does anyone actually picture Margaret Hamiltonâ€™s nipples when they read it? (And if they did, would they get a sensation of coldness?) No. It becomes colderthanawitchestit in their brains. This is why we need to continually search for new, surprising metaphors and details. We canâ€™t evoke the heroâ€™s strength by mentioning his rippling biceps, but we may be able to do it by mentioning that he lifted a hospital bed as if it was a childâ€™s cot.</p>

<p>The other trap is over-sensualizing. Imagine never being able to get to dessert because the chef, unsure that heâ€™s really earned the right to move on from the main course, keeps serving you more and more steak. Imagine having to stop and examine each pea in a side of peas and carrots. Enough already! And some aspects of the meal arenâ€™t really parts of the meal. Theyâ€™re just scaffolding to make the meal possible. The smudge on the wine glass might be memorable, but itâ€™s gratuitous if the point of the experience is the Pino Noir.</p>

<p>So how do we know which details to sensualize and which to just report in the abstract. Is it okay to say â€œHe pulled the letter out of the mailbox,â€ or do we need to describe the mailboxâ€™s rusty hinges? Thatâ€™s where a lot of the artistry comes in. Itâ€™s an aesthetic judgement writers have to learn to make, and most improve at making it over time.</p>

<p>One key is to think about which elements are the actual plot points and which are the glue that holds those points together. Say the key points are that the hero hears the mailman drop letters into the box, reads one of the letters and learns his brother has died. The fact that he had to extract the letters from the mailbox isnâ€™t a plot point. Itâ€™s glue. It may be necessary to include it, so that the reader knows that the fictional world follows the same rules as the real world (in which mailmen stuff letters into mailboxes). Another clue is that the character doesnâ€™t need to remember it. When looking back on the moment, years later, heâ€™d probably talk about the letter that changed his life. He wouldnâ€™t necessarily recall pulling it from the mailbox.</p>

<p>With these glue-like elements, the first decision is whether we need to include them at all. Can the reader infer the mailbox from the items on either side of it, the mailman and the reading-of-the-letter? If it must be included (for the story to make sense or for rhythmic reasons â€“ maybe we want to build up suspense by pausing before the hero reads the letterâ€¦), can we add a sensual details without slowing down the narrative? Glue shouldnâ€™t necessarily be included without sensual details. We just want to make sure that such details donâ€™t slow the momentum or make the glue more important and memorable than we want it to be. If we answer all these questions in the negative, then weâ€™re free to relate the glue â€“ the mailbox â€“ as a naked fact, as just a mailbox.</p>

<p>If itâ€™s unimportant but necessary scaffolding, sometimes even the slightest detail is clutter. Is there really a point to â€œbrass doorknobâ€? Maybe it should just be â€œdoorknob.â€ IF the doorknob needs to be sensualized, it probably needs a detail more stirring than â€œbrass.â€</p>

<p>That which we sensualize will affect the reader â€“ it will titillate him, scratch him, stroke him or rub him the wrong way; that which we abstract will link two sensual details together. Link as quickly as possible. We need forks in order to eat, but the meal is about the linguini, not the cutlery.</p>

