<p>Write sensually. I started to discuss this, above, when I wrote about evoking images. You want to do more than that: you want to evoke senses. Humans are sensual creatures. I donâ€™t mean we like sex â€“ though we do. I mean we experience via seeing, hearing, smelling, tasting and touching. The more you evoke these senses in your prose, the stronger it will be. This is especially true if youâ€™re writing about abstractions. We have a hard time thinking abstractly, so the more you root your text in sensual, earthy, fleshy details, the better.</p>

<p>Metaphors will often help you here, as in â€œShe wanted to steal his love, like a thief snatching someoneâ€™s purse, clutching it to his chest, and running for dear life.â€ Stealing love is an abstraction. The point of most metaphors is to render the abstract in concrete form.</p>

