<p>In the first place, Housman is a â€˜countryâ€™ poet. His poems are full of the charm of <strong>buried villages</strong>, the nostalgia of place-names, Clunton and Clunbury, Knighton, Ludlow, â€˜on Wenlock Edgeâ€™, â€˜in summer time on Bredonâ€™, t<strong>hatched roofs</strong> and the j<strong>ingle of smithies, the wild jonquils in the pastures, the â€˜blue, remembered hillsâ€™</strong>. War poems apart, English verse of the 1910-25 period is mostly â€˜countryâ€™. The reason no doubt was that the rentier-professional class was ceasing once and for all to have any real relationship <strong>with the soil</strong>; but at any rate there prevailed then, far more than now, a kind of snobbism of belonging to the country and despising the town. England at that time was hardly more an agricultural country than it is now, but before the light industries began to spread themselves it was easier to think of it as one. Most middle-class boys grew up within sight of a farm, and naturally it was the picturesque side of farm life that appealed to themâ€“the <strong>ploughing, harvesting, stack-thrashing</strong> and so forth. Unless he has to do it himself a boy is not likely to notice the horrible drudgery of <strong>hoeing turnip, milking cows with chapped teats</strong> at four oâ€™clock in the morning, etc., etc. Just before, just after, and for that matter, during the war was the great age of the â€˜Nature poetâ€™, the heyday of Richard Jefferies and W. H. Hudson. Rupert Brookeâ€™s â€˜Grantchesterâ€™, the star poem of 1913, is nothing but <strong>an enormous gush</strong> of â€˜countryâ€™ sentiment, <strong>a sort of accumulated vomit from a stomach stuffed with place-names</strong>. Considered as a poem â€˜Grantchesterâ€™ is something worse than worthless, but as an illustration of what the thinking middle-class young of that period felt it is a valuable document.</p>

<p>What Orwell understood, consciously or not, is that itâ€™s dangerous to allow too many non-imagistic words to come between imagery. You can certainly discuss abstractions, but you must earn that right. A chapped teat or two will help the reader digest a sentence about the class system. Of course, in good writing, sensual details arenâ€™t gratuitous: theyâ€™re not spoons full of sugar to help the medicine go down; theyâ€™re the means through which ideas are spread.</p>

<p>Notice that Orwell both uses literal imagery, such as â€œthatched roofsâ€ and imagery as metaphor, such as â€œa sort of accumulated vomit from the stomach stuffed with place-names.â€ This is the chief purpose of metaphor: it allows you to link the abstract to the concrete. Itâ€™s an amazing human invention, because it ensured that with skill, you can express the most abstract ideasâ€”even mathematical ideasâ€”with sensual hooks that snare hungry parts of the brain.</p>

<p>Orwell evokes sounds (â€œtinklesâ€), sights (â€œwild jonquilsâ€), possibly smells (â€œwild jonquils,â€ again, and â€œaccumulated vomitâ€), textures (â€œchapped teatsâ€), flavors (â€œmilkâ€), and movements (â€œhoeingâ€, â€œstack-thrashingâ€). He, like Shakespeare and most of the writers we call â€œgreatâ€ seems to naturally think in images. We canâ€™t all be gifted that way, but we can allâ€”via re-draftingâ€”shove our writing in a sensual direction.</p>

